(See also 
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FE898F89E609FF74" box="[260,323,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
