<subSubSection id="C30CE68AFFD6FF16FF1A8E32E2D6FCA9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="key">
<keyStep id="30E2ADA4FFD6FF16FF1A8E32E2D6FEF1" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8E32E2D6FEB4" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" box="[151,1436,256,278]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8E32E2D6FEB4" box="[151,1436,256,278]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
1. Pereopods 3–7 dactylus short, with curved robust seta countering short curved unguis, (pre-stubby, 
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FB118E32E3ADFEB7" box="[1180,1255,256,278]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1 b</figureCitation>
)............. 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8E2CE2D6FEF1" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8E2CE2D6FEF1" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
- Pereopods 3–7(6) dactylus and unguis strongly modified and complex, with curved robust seta countering modified unguis, (stubby, 
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FEB98E09E63DFEF0" box="[308,375,315,337]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs1a</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FE0D8E09E6ECFEF0" box="[384,422,315,337]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1891,1915]" captionTargetBox="[164,1420,194,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-15@65.[151,1436,181,1867]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 38. Glandulotiron griffithsi gen. et sp. nov. Holotype, ♀. gp1–2, gnathopods 1 and 2; p3, pereopod 3; p5–7, pereopods 5–7 (5 broken distal to carpus); s, heavily plumose setae; x, pereopod 6 apex of propodus with stubby dactylus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572111" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572111/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">38x</figureCitation>
).................................................................................. 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30E2ADA4FFD6FF16FF1A8E6AE2D6FDA1" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8E6AE2D6FE2A" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8E6AE2D6FE2A" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
2. Head in lateral view evenly curved to downward pointed acute rostrum, eyes and accessory eyes present, coxal plate 3 rectangular, uropod 1 outer ramus of single article, reaching well beyond uropod 2..................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FFD6FF16FB458E44E2D6FE2A" authority="Lilljeborg, 1865" authorityName="Lilljeborg" authorityYear="1865" box="[1224,1436,373,395]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Tiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FB458E44E3B1FE2A" box="[1224,1275,374,395]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Tiron</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF87C8F0FFD6FF16FA8C8E47E2D6FE2A" author="Lilljeborg, W." box="[1281,1436,373,395]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref49856" refString="Lilljeborg, W. (1865) On the Lysianassa magellanica H. Milne Edwards, and on the Crustacea of the suborder Amphipoda and subfamily Lysianassina found an [sic] the coast of Sweden and Norway. Nova Acta Regiae Societatis Scientiarum Upsaliensis, Series 3, 61, 1 - 38. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 6806" type="journal article" year="1865">Lilljeborg, 1865</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8EA1E2D6FDA1" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8EA1E2D6FDA1" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
- Head in lateral view with anterior front rounded, dorsal and anterior margins straight, at right angle; rostrum apex sharply pointed at 90° angle; interantennal lateral head margin with about 100° blunt projection; coxal plate 3 widening distally to broadly rounded apex and slight posterodistal concavity; uropod 1 barely reaching end of uropod 2, uropod 3 outer ramus of single article........................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FFD6FF16FB688ED9E276FDA1" authority="Just, 2022" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[1253,1340,491,512]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Tironella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FB688ED9E276FDA1" box="[1253,1340,491,512]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Tironella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FACF8ED9E2D6FDA1" bold="true" box="[1346,1436,491,512]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A251D468FFD6FF16FACF8ED9E2D6FDA1" box="[1346,1436,491,512]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30E2ADA4FFD6FF16FF1A8D3AE2D6FDF8" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8D3AE2D6FD9A" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8D3AE2D6FD9A" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">3. Mandible palp present; uropod 3 outer ramus with small article 2, uropod peduncles, and telson with rows of elongate glands....................................................................................................4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8D71E2D6FDF8" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" box="[151,1436,579,601]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8D71E2D6FDF8" box="[151,1436,579,601]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">- Mandible palp absent; uropod 3 outer ramus of single article, urosome without glands............................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30E2ADA4FFD6FF16FF1A8D52E2D6FD32" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8D52E2D6FDD7" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" box="[151,1436,608,630]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8D52E2D6FDD7" box="[151,1436,608,630]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
4. Mandible palp article 2 straight; coxal plates 3–4 pelagont (see key to family, notes and 
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FBA28D52E328FDD7" box="[1071,1122,608,630]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[160,1423,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure-15@9.[151,1436,179,1806]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 1. Representative habitus illustrations of tironin genera. Tiron spiniferus (from Sars, 1895 pl. 140, ♀ 8 mm); Pseudotiron miratus sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 4.5 mm); Tironella pervicax comb. nov. (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 84, ♂ 4.7 mm); Glandulotiron pilocaputis sp. nov. (this paper, ♀, 6.3 mm); Metatiron tropakis (from J.L. Barnard, 1967 fig. 45, ♀, 4.9 mm); Minitiron bellairsi comb. nov. (from Just, 1981 fig. 1, ♀ 2.4 mm). a and b, dactylus and unguis of pereopods 3–7: a, stubby; b, pre-stubby." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572025/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig.1</figureCitation>
).. 
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FB058D53E3DDFDD7" box="[1160,1175,609,630]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">P</emphasis>
s 
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FB2D8D52E3B6FDD4" box="[1184,1276,608,629]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">eudotiron</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF87C8F0FFD6FF16FA8E8D52E2D6FDD7" author="Chevreux, E." box="[1283,1436,608,630]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="165 - 170" refId="ref48758" refString="Chevreux, E. (1895) Sur un Amphipode, Pseudotiron bouvieri, nov. gen. et sp., de la Famille des Syrrhoidae nouvelle pour la Fauna Mediterranenne. Bulletin de la Societe Zoologique de France, 20, 165 - 170. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 29691" type="journal article" year="1895">Chevreux, 1895</bibRefCitation>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8D4CE2D6FD32" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" box="[151,1436,637,659]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8D4CE2D6FD32" box="[151,1436,637,659]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
- Mandible palp article 2 curved, coxal plates 3–4 similar, not pelagont......................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FFD6FF16FB398D4FE276FD33" authority="Just, 2022" authorityName="Just" authorityYear="2022" box="[1204,1340,637,658]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Glandulotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FB398D4FE276FD33" box="[1204,1340,637,658]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Glandulotiron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9626913FFD6FF16FACF8D4CE2D6FD32" bold="true" box="[1346,1436,638,659]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A251D468FFD6FF16FACF8D4CE2D6FD32" box="[1346,1436,638,659]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="30E2ADA4FFD6FF16FF1A8DA9E2D6FCA9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<paragraph id="8BA9B501FFD6FF16FF1A8DA9E2D6FD6C" blockId="7.[151,1437,256,777]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<keyLead id="30E71634FFD6FF16FF1A8DA9E2D6FD6C" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
5. Gnathopod 1 basis straight (
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FE7D8DA9E508FD10" box="[496,578,667,689]" captionStart="FIGURE 43" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1845,1869]" captionTargetBox="[162,1414,195,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-23@76.[151,1436,181,1821]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 43. Principal characters separating Metatiron and Minitiron gen. nov. Upper row, gnathopod 1; lower row, maxilla 1 outer plate. a and b, Metatiron tropakis, original; c and d, Minitiron bellairsi, c from Just 1981; d, from Barnard &amp; Thomas 1989." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572127" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572127/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 43a</figureCitation>
), maxilla 1 outer plate with broad oblique row of spine-setae (
<figureCitation id="132DA984FFD6FF16FB158DA9E3A3FD10" box="[1176,1257,667,689]" captionStart="FIGURE 43" captionStartId="76.[151,250,1845,1869]" captionTargetBox="[162,1414,195,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-23@76.[151,1436,181,1821]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 43. Principal characters separating Metatiron and Minitiron gen. nov. Upper row, gnathopod 1; lower row, maxilla 1 outer plate. a and b, Metatiron tropakis, original; c and d, Minitiron bellairsi, c from Just 1981; d, from Barnard &amp; Thomas 1989." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6572127" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6572127/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 43b</figureCitation>
)......................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C16CE82FFD6FF16FBF78D8BE2D6FD6C" authority="Rabindranath, 1972" authorityName="Rabindranath" authorityYear="1972" box="[1146,1436,696,718]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Metatiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
